summary: Let’s Talk About Pokemon - The Solosis Family
title: Let’s Talk About Pokemon - The Solosis Family
body:
577: Solosis

And in which I’ve given my grievances about weird humanoid Pokemon last time, today I’m sure you may know where I would take this line after I’ve said I love me a good slime monster. Yeah, of these two version exclusives, the Solosis line certainly takes the cake for me. This supersized cell friend is so psychologically advanced that it doesn’t even need to develop a properly full body. It really is just a floating cell with a protective gelatinous membrane. And it’s just. So darn cute.

Personal Score: 8/10

Single-celled perfection

578: Duosion

Duosion here is sadly pretty middle-stage, but is nonetheless a pretty nice design anyways. Suitably, the “mitosis” Pokemon has become two separate bodies in the same cell “body”, albeit on the the bodies is severely underplayed and is more like a floating headcrest than anything. It also apparently has two independently thinking brains, which causes trouble when they disagree but amplifies their powers when they’re in synch.

Personal Score: 8/10

Maybe just lacking the charm of Solosis and the cool-factor of the final stage, but hey. I’ll still give it an 8.

579: Reuniclus

And here comes Reuniclus, an all-around really cool, gelatinous “slime”, embryonic cell monster. For one thing, the sight of the blobby body with tinier bodies floating inside of itself is a cool enough visual even outside of this Pokemon. Reuniclus always really called the Goolix from Pikmin to mind. Atop everything, this has to be one of the cooler ideas for Psychic types. It also manages to be both cool and cute as well. They also supposedly have a whole network of brains this time around too, even hinted at that network of brains being inside the orbs that make up their arms.

A really cool visual of a Pokemon that is perhaps just shy of being a top favorite of mine, but hey. I still love me this jelly friend. I’m still, however, gonna be waiting for that purely gelatinous slime creature. I’ll probably love it no matter the shape it takes.

Personal Score: 9/10

Ya Psychic-powered Jelly Bear.

Overall:

A really solid idea for a Pokemon, more or less fully realized in the final evolution that doesn’t tarnish the appeal of the whole line, thankfully.

blog.name: pokegodsandmissingno
blog.title: P̵o̵K̸é̴G̸o̸D̷s̸ and Frightful Things to Come?
blog.description: There is a growing desire and expectation of humans here on Earth in making full contact with PoKéMoN who are still unknown. Back in 1995, when I saw my first UPM (Unindexed Pocket Monster), I found out very quickly that other people thought you were totally crazy if you said you saw such things. The world has changed quite a bit since then when I was a child. In fact, in late 1997, a poll taken in Kanto shows that for the first time ever, more than fifty percent of residents now believe in PokéGODS's. Since then, there have been polls that put the figure at over eighty percent or more.

summary: My Espeon, Fortune, keeps trying to get into my pantry and steal treats with her Psychic abilities; even if I hide them on the...
question: My Espeon, Fortune, keeps trying to get into my pantry and steal treats with her Psychic abilities; even if I hide them on the top shelf, she just floats the box down. We have behavioral lessons scheduled for next week, but until we solve the problem, should I invest in a lock on the pantry door, or is that overkill? Or, alternatively, not overkill enough?
answer:
Well, if it is overkill, what is it hurting?

And if it is not enough, what will be?
